32
00:04:19,686 --> 00:04:21,038
Right now we're seeing an accident

33
00:04:21,038 --> 00:04:22,490
on the southbound Tristate

34
00:04:22,490 --> 00:04:25,280
just south of 68th and 70 Road.

35
00:04:25,280 --> 00:04:27,085
We have one lane blocked at the corner

36
00:04:27,085 --> 00:04:31,085
so we're seeing some
slight delays in that area.

37
00:04:39,286 --> 00:04:41,369
- Good morning.
- Morning.

38
00:04:44,340 --> 00:04:45,663
What?

39
00:04:45,663 --> 00:04:48,167
- You were watching Wake
Up Chicago, weren't you?

40
00:04:48,167 --> 00:04:49,140
- Oh, I didn't notice.

41
00:04:49,140 --> 00:04:50,923
I just turned the TV on.

42
00:04:52,095 --> 00:04:53,339
- [Carrie] Mmhmm.

43
00:04:53,339 --> 00:04:54,810
- What's the matter?

44
00:04:54,810 --> 00:04:57,480
- Well it appears my wife
is a morning news adulterer.

45
00:04:57,480 --> 00:04:59,810
- I'm not, it's just the forecast

46
00:04:59,810 --> 00:05:02,090
is more accurate on Channel 14.

47
00:05:02,090 --> 00:05:04,690
- So I guess a little
solidarity is too much to ask?

48
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:07,300
- It's just the weather.
- Yeah.

49
00:05:07,300 --> 00:05:10,310
Well keep in mind, my ratings
determine my marketability.

50
00:05:10,310 --> 00:05:11,750
And if I can't draw the locals,

51
00:05:11,750 --> 00:05:13,650
how am I supposed to lure the nation?

52
00:05:13,650 --> 00:05:16,500
- The same way you have
for the last 15 years,

53
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:18,563
with that beautiful smile of yours.

54
00:05:20,110 --> 00:05:21,520
- Well, beautiful smiles are

55
00:05:21,520 --> 00:05:23,980
a dime a dozen in this industry.

56
00:05:23,980 --> 00:05:26,700
A month ago, I had three
national networks scouting me,

57
00:05:26,700 --> 00:05:29,410
and not one of them's expressed interest.

58
00:05:29,410 --> 00:05:31,760
- Not yet, I'm sure you'll
hear something soon.

59
00:05:33,310 --> 00:05:34,143
- Thank you.

60
00:05:35,302 --> 00:05:37,255
- [TV Announcer] Do you suffer
from excessive heartburn,

61
00:05:37,255 --> 00:05:38,767
acid reflux, indigestion--

62
00:05:38,767 --> 00:05:40,310
- You okay?

63
00:05:40,310 --> 00:05:42,440
- Yeah, I'm just a little tired.

64
00:05:42,440 --> 00:05:43,970
- Well why don't you take a few days off?

65
00:05:43,970 --> 00:05:45,720
It'll be good for you.

66
00:05:45,720 --> 00:05:46,800
- I'm all right, it's just some nights

67
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:48,430
are longer than others.

68
00:05:48,430 --> 00:05:50,670
- Well yeah, you're pulling
10 hour shifts at the hospital

69
00:05:50,670 --> 00:05:52,500
and then you're racing home
to take care of me and Brian

70
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:55,200
like we're not capable
of fending for ourselves.

71
00:05:55,200 --> 00:05:56,313
- I'm fine, really.

72
00:05:57,640 --> 00:06:02,090
- Look Audrey, I know
how stubborn you can be,

73
00:06:02,090 --> 00:06:04,040
but if the job is
becoming too much for you,

74
00:06:04,040 --> 00:06:06,763
I need you to be rational
enough to let it go, okay?

75
00:06:07,630 --> 00:06:10,800
I made a vow to take care
of you and Brian, remember?

76
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:11,683
- Of course.

77
00:06:13,240 --> 00:06:14,580
- So let me.

78
00:06:14,580 --> 00:06:16,110
We're in a good place financially.

79
00:06:16,110 --> 00:06:18,030
You don't have to work so hard.

80
00:06:18,030 --> 00:06:18,863
- I love what I do.

81
00:06:18,863 --> 00:06:19,760
It's my profession.

82
00:06:21,390 --> 00:06:22,290
- Of course it is.

83
00:06:23,947 --> 00:06:25,410
I gotta get goin'.

84
00:06:25,410 --> 00:06:27,470
- No wait, let me make you lunch first.

85
00:06:27,470 --> 00:06:30,240
- It's okay, I'll just have
Rosie grab me something, okay?

86
00:06:30,240 --> 00:06:31,841
Hey.

87
00:06:31,841 --> 00:06:34,440
Just take it easy today, okay?

88
00:06:34,440 --> 00:06:35,340
- [Audrey] I will.

89
00:06:37,399 --> 00:06:38,232
- Love you.

90
00:06:38,232 --> 00:06:39,065
- [Audrey] Love you too.

91
00:06:40,676 --> 00:06:45,009
- [Carrie] See you later
this afternoon, sweetheart.

92
00:06:46,730 --> 00:06:48,623
- I hope you're nearly done up there.

93
00:06:49,808 --> 00:06:52,475
(phone ringing)

94
00:06:58,410 --> 00:06:59,243
Hello?

95
00:07:01,370 --> 00:07:03,769
No, I'm just gonna catch up on some sleep.

96
00:07:03,769 --> 00:07:05,804
(gentle music)

97
00:07:05,804 --> 00:07:07,387
What are you doing?

98
00:07:12,515 --> 00:07:14,968
- [TV Reporter] According
to Mount Sinai Hospital--

99
00:07:14,968 --> 00:07:17,288
- Hey, let me call you back.
- Missing child advocate,

100
00:07:17,288 --> 00:07:19,846
Valerie Whitaker has passed away.

101
00:07:19,846 --> 00:07:21,831
Doctors say she died late last night

102
00:07:21,831 --> 00:07:23,363
from heart complications.

103
00:07:23,363 --> 00:07:25,989
You may recall a little over a decade ago

104
00:07:25,989 --> 00:07:27,477
when our network first
brought you coverage

105
00:07:27,477 --> 00:07:29,340
of the young, recovering drug addict.

106
00:07:29,340 --> 00:07:34,340
- I understand that what I
did was selfish, and immoral.

107
00:07:37,160 --> 00:07:39,710
And that nothing in this world can justify

108
00:07:39,710 --> 00:07:42,640
me selling my child to people

109
00:07:42,640 --> 00:07:44,273
in conditions unknown.

110
00:07:45,520 --> 00:07:46,920
My only hope is

111
00:07:47,809 --> 00:07:48,759
that my little boy,

112
00:07:50,460 --> 00:07:51,753
wherever he is,

113
00:07:53,140 --> 00:07:57,410
can find it in his heart
to forgive me. (sobbing)

114
00:07:57,410 --> 00:07:58,730
- [TV Reporter] Following that interview,

115
00:07:58,730 --> 00:08:01,640
Valerie Whitaker set out on
a national media campaign

116
00:08:01,640 --> 00:08:02,523
to find her son.

117
00:08:04,231 --> 00:08:05,064
- Mom?

118
00:08:05,903 --> 00:08:06,736
- Hi.

119
00:08:08,884 --> 00:08:11,717
(sorrowful music)

120
00:08:28,607 --> 00:08:29,453
- You okay?

121
00:08:30,580 --> 00:08:32,970
- Your breakfast is on the table.

122
00:08:32,970 --> 00:08:35,260
Do you want milk or O.J?

123
00:08:35,260 --> 00:08:36,093
- O.J.'s good.

124
00:08:36,093 --> 00:08:38,831
(bookbag thumps)

125
00:08:40,910 --> 00:08:41,960
You sure you're okay?

126
00:08:43,090 --> 00:08:44,120
- [Audrey] Yeah, I'm fine.

127
00:08:44,120 --> 00:08:45,763
I was just watching the news.

128
00:08:46,700 --> 00:08:47,533
- What happened?

129
00:08:49,275 --> 00:08:51,860
(liquid pouring)

130
00:08:51,860 --> 00:08:52,693
- Nothing.

131
00:08:54,530 --> 00:08:55,680
When's your next match?

132
00:08:56,860 --> 00:08:58,660
- The semifinals are Thursday night.

133
00:09:00,850 --> 00:09:02,750
- As in tomorrow night?

134
00:09:02,750 --> 00:09:03,583
- Yeah.

135
00:09:05,180 --> 00:09:06,740
- I thought I told you
to tell me these things

136
00:09:06,740 --> 00:09:08,806
at least a week in advance?

137
00:09:08,806 --> 00:09:10,780
- I thought you knew.

138
00:09:10,780 --> 00:09:13,460
- How would I know if you hadn't told me?

139
00:09:13,460 --> 00:09:15,190
- Mom knew about it.

140
00:09:15,190 --> 00:09:16,680
- Oh, and that's how you
keep me informed these days,

141
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:18,190
through your mom?

142
00:09:18,190 --> 00:09:20,793
- I just thought maybe you
guys had talked about it.

143
00:09:20,793 --> 00:09:21,923
- Well we haven't.

144
00:09:23,140 --> 00:09:25,780
- So do you have work
tomorrow night or something?

145
00:09:25,780 --> 00:09:27,960
- Yeah, I'm scheduled to.

146
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:31,092
You need to start telling
me these things sooner.

147
00:09:31,092 --> 00:09:31,925
- Okay.

148
00:09:33,090 --> 00:09:33,923
- I mean it, Brian.

149
00:09:33,923 --> 00:09:35,360
I don't wanna miss another match

150
00:09:35,360 --> 00:09:37,317
because you don't care
enough to tell me in advance.

151
00:09:37,317 --> 00:09:39,343
- All right Mom, geez.

152
00:09:41,110 --> 00:09:41,943
- Sorry.

153
00:09:51,734 --> 00:09:54,643
(door closing)

154
00:09:54,643 --> 00:09:57,143
(crow cawing)

155
00:10:04,190 --> 00:10:05,023
Bye.

156
00:10:17,139 --> 00:10:18,971
(crow cawing)

157
00:10:18,971 --> 00:10:20,487
(door closing)

158
00:10:20,487 --> 00:10:23,705
(sinister music)

159
00:10:23,705 --> 00:10:27,122
(computer keys clicking)

160
00:10:31,920 --> 00:10:33,530
- So your parents put
you out of their home

161
00:10:33,530 --> 00:10:37,000
at the age of 17, with no
other means of support.

162
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:40,030
Which you've stated, led
to a life of drug abuse,

163
00:10:40,030 --> 00:10:43,180
alcoholism, even prostitution.

164
00:10:43,180 --> 00:10:44,960
But how did you get to the point

165
00:10:44,960 --> 00:10:46,993
of actually selling your newborn child?

166
00:10:55,361 --> 00:10:58,528
- There's no legitimate reason for it.

167
00:11:02,640 --> 00:11:04,023
I was an addict.

168
00:11:05,986 --> 00:11:09,353
(sighs) I lived so recklessly at the time.

169
00:11:11,280 --> 00:11:12,510
My only concern

170
00:11:13,560 --> 00:11:17,200
was my next hit.

171
00:11:17,200 --> 00:11:18,873
I would do anything to get it.

172
00:11:21,160 --> 00:11:25,077
- So several years pass, and
you pay your debt to society.

173
00:11:25,077 --> 00:11:27,110
And now you're referred to

174
00:11:27,110 --> 00:11:28,983
as a crusader for missing children.

175
00:11:31,200 --> 00:11:32,450
What do you make of that?

176
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:35,070
- [Valerie] I never anticipated

177
00:11:35,070 --> 00:11:38,930
that outpouring of national
support to begin with,

178
00:11:38,930 --> 00:11:41,583
so it all sort of came
as a surprise to me.

179
00:11:42,980 --> 00:11:45,100
- [Reporter] So this isn't
just some sort of ploy

180
00:11:45,100 --> 00:11:46,900
to win the affections of the public?

181
00:11:49,150 --> 00:11:50,003
- Not at all.

182
00:11:52,740 --> 00:11:54,660
The only reason I launched my campaign

183
00:11:54,660 --> 00:11:56,163
was to find my son.

184
00:11:57,328 --> 00:11:58,411
Nothing more.

185
00:11:59,860 --> 00:12:03,610
- So tell me, does it
ever bother you at all?

186
00:12:03,610 --> 00:12:06,920
I can't even imagine
how difficult it must be

187
00:12:06,920 --> 00:12:09,280
to play such a huge role in reuniting

188
00:12:09,280 --> 00:12:11,313
a family with a missing child,

189
00:12:12,370 --> 00:12:15,023
and still have no success
in finding your own.

190
00:12:22,564 --> 00:12:25,397
- (sniffles) Yes.

191
00:12:29,250 --> 00:12:31,013
It is very difficult.

192
00:12:33,598 --> 00:12:35,848
(sniffles)

193
00:12:39,377 --> 00:12:42,613
But I do believe that I will find him.

194
00:12:48,140 --> 00:12:48,973
I have to.

195
00:12:54,616 --> 00:12:57,699
(rock music playing)

196
00:13:04,136 --> 00:13:06,658
(car door slamming)

197
00:13:06,658 --> 00:13:09,120
(woman speaking over loudspeaker)

198
00:13:09,120 --> 00:13:11,640
- (knocks on door) Morning.

199
00:13:11,640 --> 00:13:12,740
- [School Secretary]
Morning, can I help you?

200
00:13:12,740 --> 00:13:14,220
- I'm a private investigator here

201
00:13:14,220 --> 00:13:16,373
to pick up some court ordered documents.

202
00:13:18,140 --> 00:13:19,250
- Do you know who you spoke with?

203
00:13:19,250 --> 00:13:20,083
- Sure.

204
00:13:22,070 --> 00:13:23,633
It's Gloria Patterson.

205
00:13:24,960 --> 00:13:27,233
- Okay, give me a moment please.

206
00:13:30,640 --> 00:13:31,473
Ms. Patterson?

207
00:13:32,771 --> 00:13:35,293
Yeah, there is an investigator here.

208
00:13:36,890 --> 00:13:38,170
All right.

209
00:13:38,170 --> 00:13:39,293
Sure, thanks.

210
00:13:40,830 --> 00:13:42,080
She'll be right with you.

211
00:13:46,530 --> 00:13:47,610
- Eric Reese, I presume?

212
00:13:47,610 --> 00:13:48,770
- [Eric] Yes.

213
00:13:48,770 --> 00:13:50,720
- Can I see some identification please.

214
00:13:54,530 --> 00:13:55,363
Thank you.

215
00:13:58,177 --> 00:13:59,010
He's a brilliant young man,

216
00:13:59,010 --> 00:14:00,614
it's nothing serious, I hope?

217
00:14:00,614 --> 00:14:03,364
(sinister music)

218
00:14:04,220 --> 00:14:05,053
- Thank you.

219
00:14:05,053 --> 00:14:06,248
(woman speaking over loudspeaker)

220
00:14:06,248 --> 00:14:08,915
(phone ringing)

221
00:14:09,860 --> 00:14:12,777
(car horn honking)

222
00:14:35,422 --> 00:14:38,089
(phone ringing)

223
00:14:48,647 --> 00:14:50,170
- Okay, and Tyler's still with you.

224
00:14:50,170 --> 00:14:53,120
Okay, I'll be there in
like 15, 20 minutes.

225
00:14:53,120 --> 00:14:54,180
Okay.

226
00:14:54,180 --> 00:14:56,530
Yeah, okay, okay, I'm on my way now.

227
00:14:56,530 --> 00:14:57,363
- Is everything okay?

228
00:14:57,363 --> 00:14:59,210
- I'm so sorry, my sitter has an emergency

229
00:14:59,210 --> 00:15:00,810
and there was no one else I could call.

230
00:15:00,810 --> 00:15:02,430
- It's okay, I got some shut eye.

231
00:15:02,430 --> 00:15:03,570
- I appreciate it.
- No problem.

232
00:15:03,570 --> 00:15:04,990
Hey, I was gonna ask you, tomorrow night,

233
00:15:04,990 --> 00:15:05,890
Brian has a match--

234
00:15:05,890 --> 00:15:07,040
- No worries, I got it.

235
00:15:07,040 --> 00:15:07,873
- You sure?

236
00:15:07,873 --> 00:15:08,820
- I'll see you on Friday.

237
00:15:08,820 --> 00:15:09,653
- Thank you.

238
00:15:13,387 --> 00:15:17,554
(woman speaking over loudspeaker)

239
00:15:37,970 --> 00:15:39,960
- Do you mind if I sit here?

240
00:15:39,960 --> 00:15:40,810
- Go ahead.

241
00:15:40,810 --> 00:15:41,643
- Thanks.

242
00:15:48,840 --> 00:15:50,490
You know, normally I
don't like hospital food,

243
00:15:50,490 --> 00:15:52,030
but these salads are,

244
00:15:52,030 --> 00:15:52,863
they're okay.

245
00:16:00,440 --> 00:16:02,390
Didn't expect to see you here so early.

246
00:16:04,310 --> 00:16:05,536
- I'm sorry, do I know you?

247
00:16:05,536 --> 00:16:06,962
- Mmm mmm.

248
00:16:06,962 --> 00:16:08,620
We haven't met, I'm Eric.

249
00:16:08,620 --> 00:16:10,640
How are you?

250
00:16:10,640 --> 00:16:12,230
- Audrey.

251
00:16:12,230 --> 00:16:13,810
- I know.

252
00:16:13,810 --> 00:16:16,110
I've learned quite a bit about you.

253
00:16:16,110 --> 00:16:16,943
- Have you?

254
00:16:19,330 --> 00:16:20,163
- Yeah.

255
00:16:20,163 --> 00:16:21,253
And from what I gather,

256
00:16:23,330 --> 00:16:24,380
you're a good person.

257
00:16:28,200 --> 00:16:33,200
But I'm really more concerned
with what people don't know.

258
00:16:39,230 --> 00:16:40,330
- Really, why is that?

259
00:16:41,366 --> 00:16:42,766
- It's just part of the job.

260
00:16:45,690 --> 00:16:48,373
- I see, well I better get back to work.

261
00:16:49,360 --> 00:16:50,410
- I know about Brian.

262
00:16:54,710 --> 00:16:55,543
- Who are you?

263
00:16:56,620 --> 00:16:57,803
- Private investigator.

264
00:16:59,590 --> 00:17:03,020
I was hired by the Whitaker estate to--

265
00:17:03,020 --> 00:17:04,080
- Whitaker, who?

266
00:17:05,430 --> 00:17:06,433
- Valerie Whitaker.

267
00:17:07,510 --> 00:17:08,343
Her family.

268
00:17:09,980 --> 00:17:12,440
- How long have you been following me?

269
00:17:12,440 --> 00:17:13,433
- Just a few days.

270
00:17:15,040 --> 00:17:16,780
Got a call to check out a lead

271
00:17:16,780 --> 00:17:19,030
that another detective
came across in Boston.

